Description: Atmospheric pressure reduced to sea level using temperature profile of the standard atmosphere. Given in inches of Mercury (in Hg).
This is the dew point temperature. It is given here in whole degrees Fahrenheit.
This is the dry-bulb temperature and is commonly used as the standard air temperature reported. It is given here in whole degrees Fahrenheit.

Amount of precipitation in inches to hundredths over the past hour. For certain automated stations, precipitation will be reported at sub-hourly intervals (e.g. every 15 or 20 minutes) as an accumulated amount of all precipitation within the preceding hour. A 'T' indicates a trace amount of precipitation
Weather types describe precipitation or obstructions to vision occurring at the time of observation. These are reported by automated sensors (AU or AW) and manually (MW) by human observation.
Difference in pressure over the past 3 hours. Prefixed with a + or - to indicate increase or decrease in pressure respectively. Given in inches of Mercury (in Hg).

Pressure tendency (In general a 0 through 3 here indicates an increase in pressure over previous 3 hours and a 5 through 8 indicates a decrease over the previous 3 hours and 4 indicates no change during the previous 3 hours).
This is the relative humidity given to the nearest whole percentage.
A report of each cloud layer
Sea level pressure given in inches of Mercury (in Hg).
Atmospheric pressure observed at the station during the time of observation. Given in inches of Mercury (in Hg).
The horizontal distance an object can be seen and identified given in whole miles. Note visibilities less than 3 miles are usually given in smaller increments (e.g. 2.5).
This is the wet-bulb temperature. It is given here in whole degrees Fahrenheit.
Wind direction from true north using compass directions (e.g. 360 = true north, 180 = south, 270 = west, etc.). Note: A direction of 000 is given for calm winds.
Wind gusts occurring during time of observation. Given in miles per hour (mph).
Speed of the wind at the time of observation given in miles per hour (mph).
Time of sunrise using a 24-hour clock (Local Standard Time Daylight Savings Time is not used)
Time of sunset using a 24-hour clock (Local Standard Time Daylight Savings Time is not used)
Average daily dew point temperature (in whole degrees Fahrenheit)
Average temperature for the day (in whole degrees Fahrenheit). This is based on the arithmetic average of the maximum and minimum temperature for the day
Average daily relative humidity (in whole percent)

Maximum temperature for the day (in whole degrees Fahrenheit). An asterisk (*) is used to designate when a daily maximum temperature is also the extreme maximum for the month.
Minimum temperature for the day (in whole degrees Fahrenheit). An asterisk (*) is used to designate when a daily minimum temperature is also the extreme minimum for the month.
direction of wind during peak wind speed for the day given as direction from which wind was blowing using a 360 degree compass with respect to true north (e.g north = 360, south = 180, etc.)
peak wind speed for the day (in whole miles per hour)

Water equivalent amount of precipitation for the day (in inches to hundredths). This is all types of precipitation (melted and frozen). T indicates trace amount of precipitation. If left blank, precipitation amount is unreported.
Daily reading of snow on ground (in whole inches). T indicates trace amount.
Daily amount of snowfall (in inches to the tenths). T indicates trace amount
direction of wind during maximum sustained wind speed for the day given as direction from which wind was blowing using a 360 degree compass with respect to true north

maximum sustained wind speed for the day (in whole miles per hour). Note: For U.S. locations this is the fastest reported speed for the day that is sustained for at least 2 minutes for years 1994 and later. For earlier years it is the fastest reported speed sustained for at least 1 minute
Daily occurrences of weather types. The 2-digit number in each designation corresponds to the WT (weather type code) used in GHCN-Daily dataset.

indicates if the dekadal average temperatures were above or below the 30-year normal. It is calculated for each grid cell by subtracting the average air temperature estimated by AFWA from the 30-year normal (from 1961-1990).

defined as a departure of the mean daily temperature from a given standard: one degree day for each degree of departure above (or below) the base temperature during one day. The degree day is related to the outside temperature and is not related to time.

defined as a departure of the mean daily temperature from a given standard: one degree day for each degree of departure above (or below) the base temperature during one day. The degree day is related to the outside temperature and is not related to time.

indicates if the dekadal maximum temperatures were above or below the 30-year normal. It is calculated for each WMO station by subtracting the maximum air temperature recorded at the station from the 30-year normal (1961-1990) for the station.
The difference in degrees Fahrenheit between the forecast nighttime minimum temperature and the average minimum temperature for that station.
The cumulative rainfall departure (CRD) from normal rainfall is a concept sometimes utilized to evaluate the temporal correlation of rainfall with surface water or ground water levels.
